               <msContents>
                  <summary change="#add-summary"> An selected excerpt or abridgement of a portion of
                     the <title>Aḥvāl-i Jang-i Marhattah</title> (Events of the Maratha War) by ʻAlī
                     Ibrāhīm Khān (d. ca. 1793). It concerns events pertaining to the mid-18th
                     century to </summary>

                  <msItem xml:id="Persian_MS_452-item1">
                     <author key="person_20524990" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/20524990"
                        change="#ids-cleanup">
                        <persName xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc" type="standard">ʻAlī Ibrāhīm Khān, d. 1793
                           or 4</persName>
                     </author>
                     <title xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc" key="work_7080">Aḥvāl-i Jang-i Marhattah</title>
                     <title xml:lang="fa" key="work_7080">احوال جنگ مرهته</title>
                     <incipit xml:lang="fa" type="basmalla"><locus from="1b" to="1b"> برگ ۱پ (folio
                           1b):</locus> الحمد لله علی نعمامیهٔ و الصلو‫ة علی نبیّه و الهلبیته و
                        اصحابه این وقایٔع آثار عبرت نامه اولی الابصار است که در عهد حکومت امیر
                        والاجاه فلک بار گاه مرکز دایٔرهٔ اقبال عد و مال خورشید آسمان فطرت ناصب علام
                        رفعت و شوکت نواب مستطاب معلی القاب مشیر خاص حضور سلطان انگلیستان زبدهٔ
                        توئنان بها در عظیم ایشان گورنر بهادر دام اقاله به قلم شکسته رقم علی ابراهیم
                        خان صورت ارتسام می‌یابد... </incipit>
                     <explicit xml:lang="fa"><locus from="30a" to="30a"> برگ ۳۰ر (folio
                           30a):</locus> الحمد للّه و شکر للّه که این فهرست مجموعه خرم هوشیاراست. و
                        مد حساب مرد دیندار ایست بسال هزار و دوصد و یک هجری در بلده بنارس صورت ارتسام
                        پذیرفت. امید که پسندیده زیرگان و قبول خاطر پر و جوان گردد. </explicit>
                     <colophon>
                        <locus from="30b" to="30b"> برگ ۳۰پ (folio 30b):</locus> الحمد للَله پ المنه
                        که تواریخ اهل دکن بتاریخ سی ۳۰ ام ماه اکتوبر سنه ۱۸۶۳ عیسوی حُلیه اتمام در
                        بر کشید. </colophon>
                     <colophon>Completed on <date calendar="#Gregorian" when="1863-10-30">30 Oct.
                           1863 CE</date></colophon>
                     <textLang mainLang="fa">Persian</textLang>
                     <note>English translation by <persName role="trl"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/68992681" key="person_68992681">A. R.
                           Fuller</persName>, posthumously published by Elliot and Dowson.
                        Subsequently abridged by <persName role="abr" key="person_f6899">Munshī
                           Muḥammad Muḥsin al-Dīn</persName>. For another holograph work by this
                        same author, see <ref
                           target="https://www.fihrist.org.uk/catalog/manuscript_6811"><idno>Persian
                              MS 318</idno></ref></note>
                  </msItem>
               </msContents>
               <physDesc>
                  <objectDesc form="codex">
                     <supportDesc material="chart">
                        <support>Written on cross-grained, bone-coloured, externally sized and
                           polished, machine-made wove <material>paper</material>, probably
                           manufactured in Europe.</support>
                        <extent><measure unit="folios" quantity="32"> 32 folios, 2 flyleaves (ff. i
                              + 32 + i ii)</measure>. <dimensions type="leaf" unit="mm">
                              <height>239</height>
                              <width>156</width>
                           </dimensions>
                           <dimensions type="written" unit="mm">
                              <height>174</height>
                              <width>90</width>
                           </dimensions>
                        </extent>
                        <foliation>Foliated in pencilled Arabic numerals that start on folio
                              <locus>1Aa</locus> and every ten threafter, subsequently completed
                           when catalogued, hence under by one.</foliation>
                        <collation>Comprised of quaternions. 4IV(31)</collation>
                        <condition>Text in good condition, albeit separated from the
                           binding.</condition>
                     </supportDesc>
                     <layoutDesc>
                        <layout columns="1" ruledLines="17" n="mistara">Written in 1 column with 17
                           lines per page. Ruled with a <hi rend="italic">misṭarah</hi> hand
                           guide.</layout>
                     </layoutDesc>
                  </objectDesc>
                  <handDesc>
                     <handNote scope="major" script="nastaliq" medium="ink">Written in clear black
                        nasta‘līq with red subheaders and colophon.</handNote>
                  </handDesc>
                  <additions>
                     <lb/>
                     <label>Inscriptions:</label> The <locus from="ia" to="ia">right flyleaf a side
                        (f. ia)</locus> bears the title and author's name written in Persian, with
                     the name of prior owner <persName type="supplied" key="person_f830" role="fmo"
                        change="#role-assignment">Colonel George William Hamilton</persName>, likely
                     in the hand of his assitant <persName role="ins wst" cert="high"
                        key="person_f6587">Muhīn Dās</persName>.<lb/>
                     <label>Bookplates:</label><lb/> The <locus from="Inner_back_cover"
                        to="Inner_back_cover">left paste-down</locus>: <q xml:lang="en">Bibliotheca
                        Lindesiana</q> with shelfmark <q xml:lang="en">2/G</q>, and <q xml:lang="en"
                        >Hamilton MSS No. 369</q>. </additions>
                  <bindingDesc>
                     <binding notBefore="1863" notAfter="1868">
                        <p>Evidently rebound in <placeName cert="high"
                              ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7001535">Delhi</placeName> in a
                           hybrid British-Indian style for former owner <persName type="supplied"
                              key="person_f830" role="fmo" change="#role-assignment">Colonel George
                              William Hamilton</persName> after <date calendar="#Gregorian"
                              when="1863">1863</date> when he served there as Commissioner.</p>
                        <p>Sewn at two unsupported stations, comparatively heavy endpapers added,
                           and edges trimmed. Case-bound in full maroon goatskin
                              <material>leather</material>, tight-backed, over pasteboards, with
                           squares along the edges, defined joints, but without a flap (type III
                           binding per Déroche).</p>
                        <decoNote type="binding">Spine and board margins stained dark brown ~15mm in
                           from the edges, with diagonal painted or ruled lines in the same dye.
                           Exterior margins outlined with ruled double yellow lines on either side,
                           along with single interior lines, all in yellow. Small octagonal paper
                              <locus from="Spine" to="Spine">spine</locus> label bears the title in
                           Persian. Compare
                           with <ref target="https://www.fihrist.org.uk/catalog/manuscript_6971"
                              ><idno>Persian MS 477</idno></ref></decoNote>
                        <p><dimensions type="binding" unit="mm">
                              <height>251</height>
                              <width>161</width>
                              <depth>15</depth>
                           </dimensions></p>
                        <condition>Handle binding with caution. Textblock fully separates from the
                           cover, and the boards yawn at the fore-edge.</condition>
                     </binding>
                  </bindingDesc>
               </physDesc>
               <history>
                  <origin> Probably completed for <persName type="supplied" key="person_f830"
                        role="fmo" change="#role-assignment">Colonel George William
                        Hamilton</persName> in <origPlace
                        ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7001535" key="place_7001535">
                        Dehli</origPlace>
                     <origDate calendar="#Gregorian" when="1863-10-30">30 Oct. 1863 CE</origDate>
                  </origin>
                  <provenance>
                     <p><persName type="supplied" key="person_f830" role="fmo"
                           change="#role-assignment">Colonel George William Hamilton
                           (1807-1868)</persName> served in <placeName
                           ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7000208" key="place_7000208"
                           >India</placeName> from <date calendar="#Gregorian" from="1823" to="1867"
                           >1823 to 1867</date>, latterly as Commissioner in <placeName
                           ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7001535" key="place_7001535"
                           >Delhi</placeName> in <date calendar="#Gregorian" when="1862"
                        >1862</date>. Therefore, date of the volume's completion comports with his
                        tenure there. He acquired over a thousand Indian and Persian manuscripts,
                        from which the <orgName ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/134857252">British
                           Museum</orgName> selected 352, now held in the <orgName
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/121814978">British Library</orgName>.</p>
                  </provenance>
                  <provenance>
                     <persName role="fmo" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/97751058/" key="person_97751058"
                        > Alexander Lindsay, 25th Earl of Crawford (1812–1880)</persName> purchased
                     the remainder of Hamilton's collection in <date calendar="#Gregorian"
                        when="1868">1868</date>. </provenance>
                  <provenance><p>Purchased by <persName role="dnr" key="person_f6379"
                           change="#prov-markup">Enriqueta Rylands (1843–1908)</persName> in <date
                           calendar="#Gregorian" when="1901">1901</date> from <persName role="fmo"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/9985420/" key="person_9985420">James Ludovic
                           Lindsay, 26th Earl of Crawford (1847–1913)</persName>.</p></provenance>
                  <acquisition>
                     <p>Bequeathed by <persName key="person_f6379" change="#prov-markup">Enriqueta
                           Rylands (1843–1908)</persName> in <date calendar="#Gregorian" when="1908"
                           >1908</date> to the <orgName type="corporation" role="rps"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/312795145/">John Rylands Library</orgName>.</p>
                  </acquisition>
               </history>
